<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">FBA0015/12-13</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Associat</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">ion of British Insurers—Written </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">evidence</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The UK Insurance Industry </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK insurance industry is the third largest in the world and the largest in Europe. It is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vital part of the UK economy, managing investments amounting to 26% of the UK’s total net worth and contributing £10.4 billion in taxes to the Government. Employing over 290,000 people in the UK alone, the insurance industry is also one of this country’s m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ajor exporters, with 28% of its net premium income coming from overseas business.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Insurance helps individuals and businesses protect themselves against the everyday risks they face, enabling people to own homes, travel overseas, provide for a financially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">secure future and run businesses. Insurance underpins a healthy and prosperous society, enabling businesses and individuals to thrive, safe in the knowledge that problems can be handled and risks carefully managed. Every day, our members pay out £147 milli</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on in benefits to pensioners and long-term savers as well as £60 million in general insurance claims.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The ABI</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Association of British Insurers (ABI) is the voice of insurance, representing the general insurance, protection, investment and long-term sa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vings industry. It was formed in 1985 to represent the whole of the industry and today has over 300 members, accounting for some 90% of premiums in the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The ABI’s role is to:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 7.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• Be the voice of the UK insurance industry, leading debate and speaking up f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or insurers.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.05pt; text-indent:-7.95pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• Represent the UK insurance industry to government, regulators and policy makers in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK, EU and internationally, driving effective public policy and regulation.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.05pt; text-indent:-7.95pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• Advocate high standards of customer service within the industry and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provide useful information to the public about insurance.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.05pt; text-indent:-7.95pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">• Promote the benefits of insurance to the government, regulators, policy makers and the public.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The ABI’s Evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The ABI welcomes the opportunity to provide evidence to the House of Lords </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Economic Affairs Committee Finance Bill Sub Committee’s examination of the new approach to Tax Policy Making (“new approach”) and the extent to which it has been implemented and is delivering the objectives set out.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Government’s new approach which was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> published at the June 2010 Budget was designed to improve the predictability and stability of the tax system with consultation and scrutiny as the cornerstones.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The new approach’s aim was to introduce a longer and more considered policy cycle for changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to tax legislation. It also aimed to add scrutiny by publishing draft legislation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> months before the formal Parliamentary processes commenced.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This can be contrasted with the process it replaced which was seen by many as being piecemeal, reactive, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">predictable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which sometimes resulted in business being inadvertently impacted. In particular it involved a compressed policy cycle which could result in insufficien</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tly considered legislation as well as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> problems and extra costs for business in implemen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ting new measures. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In March 2011 the Government published a new framework</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on their approach to consultation for most tax policy changes. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The way the process has worked for policies covered by the framewor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">k has generally been as follows:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">announcement at the Budget of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e Government’s policy proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Consultation through the summer on the policy proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Publication of responses to the consultation and draft F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inance Bill clauses in December</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Consultation on the draft Finance Bill clause</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Publication of the Finance Bill in March/April</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the ABI’s experience the new approach has distinct advantages over the previous process. It is materially reducing the chances of business being inadvertently impacted by policy proposals and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ibuting to an improvement in the quality of legislation and to the building of trust between Government and business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One of the most significant recent consultations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> affecting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">insurers,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has been that on ‘modernising the taxation of corporate debt and der</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ivative contracts’. In many respects, this</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> particular consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has to date been exemplary and provides some significant examples of the new process reducing inadvertent impacts on business.  Among a variety of proposals it included changes to ‘perpetua</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l debt’ and to ‘bond funds’.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he new process has allowed constructive discussion and as a result the proposals have been modified so avoiding inadvertent impact on insurers.  Indeed, the discussion on perpetual debt enabled a wider consideration of the li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">kely impact of regulatory change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the tax relief for insurer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> regulatory debt resulting in the welcome introduction of legislation to ensure parity between insurers and banks.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The new process is undoubtedly an improvement, and it has helped to build </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> professional</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transparent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and honest relationship</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> between insurers and Government. The ABI’s view is that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to maximise the potential benefits of the new approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this is the relationship that should exist between</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Government and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">takeholders.  From the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">perspective of the ABI, there have been huge steps forward in recent years.  The consultation on the new Life Insurance Tax regime (which started before the implementation of the new approach and culminated in extensive legislation in Finance Act 2012) was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a prime example of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">constructive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> relationship</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> between Government and industry.  The resulting legislation has been well received, and given its complexity, relatively few problems have emerged as it has become embedded.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This theme of developing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the ri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ght relationship </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has also been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evident</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> during the consultation on modernising the taxation of corporate debt and derivative contracts, referred to above.  For instance, Government has listened to concerns about the proposed speed of changes to the ‘unallow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">able purpose test’ and to the ‘corporate streaming’ rules. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Consideration of any changes to both of these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rules </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been deferred to Finance Bill 2015 from the original proposal to include them in Finance Bill 2014</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, there are still areas where im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provement would be welcome. For instance, although the potential for inadvertent impact can n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ever be completely eradicated, the process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> could still usefully be finessed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in this respect </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thought given to how and when stakeholders should best be i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nvolved.  The greatest risk of inadvertent impact occurs where measures are announced at Budget with little or no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prior </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consultation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for instance due to Government concerns about forestalling.  A recent example is the legislation in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finance Act 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This legislation imposed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a premium limit o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘qualifying policies’ which was announced in principle with a commitment to consult only on the mechanics of implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but not on the policy itself</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  In policy terms it was uncle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ar whether this was an anti-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">avoidance measure or simply designed to level the playing field in respect of different savings products.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prior discussion with the insurance industry would have revealed not only that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> although simple in concept</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would be very difficult to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enact but arguably was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> little or no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tax risk for the Exchequer. Impact on insurers has included substantial systems costs and further complication of already complex legislation – one example being the need to ensure that some holders of historic endowment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mortgages were not caught with a potential tax charge at the end of their mortgage. An interesting question is whether</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> if more of the implications of the policy had been clear at the outset</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, it would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have been pursued.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, much </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their credit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> once</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">understood the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">impact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the measure, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">quickly set up</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> informal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">discussions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to identify how the process of its development might have been improved and learn lessons for the future. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We refer above to the recent consultation on ‘modernising the taxation of corporate debt and derivative contracts’.  Although it has, almost without exception, been an exemplary process, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t off on the wrong foot’ in that it started with the assumption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that change to the existing rules would be welcomed universally.  Considerable energy was therefore spent unnecessarily in challenging this assumption. Prior discussions could have prevented this and led Government to have started by asking </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">whether</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> was needed.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had been implemented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as originally proposed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> then there would have been a material negative impact on insurers. We refer above to the fact that these negative impacts were inadvertent, as far as the Governm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent were concerned, and that a number of these concerns have been alleviated during the consultation process. However, ideally it would have been better if these concerns had not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been allowed to arise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the first place, by engaging in early discussions pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ior to the proposals being announced. Thus avoiding the time consuming debate following the issue of the consultation.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This would have allowed more time for discussion of the substantive issues on which the Government wanted to make early progress</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A furt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">her example relates to the automatic exchange of information agreements the UK has entered into with the Crown Dependencies and the impending global standard for exchange of information.  Whilst the ABI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is fully supportive of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">measures</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to combat tax evasion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, at no point was there any formal consultation as to what was needed to protect the UK tax base or any consultation on the impact this would have on the competitiveness of the UK and UK business.  The conditions of these agreements, in many aspects, have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">been very difficult to rationalise with business operations and processes.  While HMRC continues to do excellent work ironing out the issues, a consultation beforehand to understand what businesses could actually achieve would have resulted in a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">better </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regime </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">whilst at the same time delivering the Government’s objectives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he three</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> month period for consultation on the draft Finance Bill is also most welcome as it gives the opportunity for any shortcomings in the legislation to be corrected. In most case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s, the ABI has been able to provide comment on legislation affecting the insurance industry, and by working with HMRC, h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> identified areas where it will not work and made suggestions for improvement to make it fit for purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In conclusion, the ABI’s vi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ew is that the new approach is most welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Not only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gone a long way towards meeting its objective of improving the predictability and stability of the tax system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, generally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> speaking, it allows the Government to meet its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">objectives without making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">implementation expensive.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Nevertheless, problems can still </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where even relatively simple legislative changes necessitate costly and time consuming system changes.  This is particularly the case for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">insurers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where changes involve products that require </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the notification of many thousands of customers.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin